{openings101.org} 1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qe6+ $6 {Played by Magnus Carlsen in several games. It's definitely a weird move - Black has blocked his central pawn and ?c8, but on the other hand gained a tempo and may later try to fianchettoe his dark-squared bishop.} 4. Be2 $1 {I believe is the strongest reply! The idea is to develop slowly by Nf3 and 0-0.} Nf6 {The most logical move. Black wants to develop with g6-?g7.} ( {simply bad is} Nc6 $2 {because of} 5. d4 {and 6. d5 is hard to meet.}  ) ( g6 5. Nf3 Bg7 6. d4 Nf6 {transposes to 4...Nf6.}  ) ( Qg6 $2 {A provocative move, which has been tried on number of occasions by my compatriots Andonov and Popchev, both of them being very fond of early originality. It is objectively dubious, Black wants to grab the g-pawn, indeed, at the cost of precious time.} 5. Nf3 $1 {The best! White is just continuing his development.} Qxg2 ( Nf6 6. O-O ( 7. d4  ) Bh3 $140 $2 7. Nh4 $1 Qg5 8. d4 Qxh4 9. g3 $18  ) 6. Rg1 Qh3 7. Bc4 {[#] Threatens ?f7+ or Ng5 at first - White is very close to winning here.} ( 8. d4 {is also strong}  ) e6 ( f6 8. d4 c6 9. Qe2 Nh6 10. d5 {White has a clear advantage.} Nf5 11. Bf4 Nh4 $2 ( {a tad better is} g5 12. Bg3 g4 13. Nd2 Bh6 14. O-O-O $16  ) 12. Nxh4 Qxh4 13. Bg3 Qh6 14. Ne4 $18 {and Black resigned on move 21 in A. Kovacevic - M. Popchev, Stara Pazova, 2007}  ) ( Nh6 8. d4 Bg4 9. Rg3 Qh5 10. Bxh6 gxh6 11. Rxg4 $1 {Wins on the spot!} Qxg4 12. Bxf7+ Kd8 ( Kxf7 13. Ne5+  ) 13. Qe2 Bg7 14. Nd5 Nc6 15. Be6 Qg6 16. Nf4 Qf6 17. Qe4 $18  ) ( h6 8. Nd5 Qd7 9. Ne5  ) 8. d4 Nf6 9. Bf1 $1 Qh5 10. Rg5 Qh6 11. Re5 Qg6 12. Bg5 Ng4 13. Nh4 $18 Qh5 $140 14. Be2  ) 5. Nf3 g6 6. d4 Bg7 7. Bf4 $1 {I prefer this move. The idea is to put immediate pressure on the opponent by attacking his c-pawn.} ( 8. O-O O-O  ) Qb6 ( {passive is} c6 8. O-O O-O 9. Re1 {and Black's queen is very badly placed.} Nd5 10. Bd3 Qd7 11. Bg5 Re8 12. Qd2 Nxc3 13. bxc3 $16 {White has a big advantage. The plan is Re4-Rae1 and even Rh4-?h6.}  ) 