{openings101.org} 1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd6 4. d4 Nf6 {The other moves are not without danger for Black, for example:} 5. Nf3 {This is in fact the initial position of the 3....Qd6 variation. Here Black has 3 main plans: 5...a6 is the old main line, which in my belief is very dubious; 5...g6, which can be labelled as the modern line and 5...c6, which is very solid and has been recently used by Magnus Carslen. The latter will be therefore our favourite, but we should also mention the Dubov's 5...Nc6.} a6 {Let me show you why I do not trust anymore this, once very popular, move!} 6. g3 $1 {The most principled way!} Bg4 ( Bf5 7. Bg2 c6 ( {much worse is} Nc6 $2 8. O-O e6 ( {Or} O-O-O 9. Ng5 Bg6 10. d5 Nb4 11. Bf4 Qc5 12. Na4 Qa5 13. c4 e6 14. a3 Nc2 15. b3 Nxa1 16. b4 Bc2 17. bxa5 Bxd1 18. Rxd1 Nb3 19. Nxf7 $18  ) 9. Bf4 Qb4 {in the view of} 10. d5 $1 O-O-O 11. a3 Qxb2 ( Qc5 12. dxc6 $1 Rxd1 13. cxb7+ Kb8 14. Rfxd1 Bd6 15. Be3 $18  ) 12. Na4 Qxc2 13. Qxc2 Bxc2 14. dxc6 Bxa4 15. cxb7+ Kb8 16. Ne5 Be8 17. Rab1 Bd6 18. Rfc1 $18  ) 8. Bf4 ( {good enough is} 9. O-O e6 10. Nh4 Bg6 11. Nxg6 hxg6 12. Na4 Nbd7 13. c4 $16  ) Qb4 9. O-O e6 ( Qxb2 $2 {loses on the spot to} 10. Na4 Qxc2 11. Qxc2 Bxc2 12. Nb6 $18  ) {and in Mamedov - Carlsen, chess24.com INT, 2020, White could seriously disturb the World Champion with} 10. Nh4 Bg6 11. Re1 $16 {and the central break is in the air.}  ) ( Nc6 $6 7. Bf4 $1 Qe6+ ( Qd8 {is probably Black's best reply, but it is an obvious concession -} 8. Bg2 e6 9. O-O Be7 10. Qe2 O-O 11. Rad1 $16  ) ( {disastrous is} Qb4 $2 8. a3 Qxb2 $2 9. Na4 $18  ) 8. Be2 $16  ) ( b5 $6 {is an attempt to oppose along the big diagonal, but the queen will find itself exposed to tactics. After the natural} 7. Bg2 Bb7 8. O-O {Black has a choice:} e6 ( c5 $6 9. Bf4 $1 Qb6 10. d5 $1 b4 $6 11. Na4 Qa5 12. c4 $1 Nbd7 ( bxc3 {leads to a hopeless Benoni after} 13. Nxc3 Nbd7 14. Nd2 $16  ) 13. Re1 $16  ) ( Nbd7 $6 9. Bf4 Qb6 10. a4 $1 b4 11. a5 {(this intermediate push is t