{openings101.org} 1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd6 4. d4 Nf6 {The other moves are not without danger for Black, for example:} 5. Nf3 {This is in fact the initial position of the 3....Qd6 variation. Here Black has 3 main plans: 5...a6 is the old main line, which in my belief is very dubious; 5...g6, which can be labelled as the modern line and 5...c6, which is very solid and has been recently used by Magnus Carslen. The latter will be therefore our favourite, but we should also mention the Dubov's 5...Nc6.} Bg4 {There are many games here. In my opinion, Black gets a very passive position.} ( Bf5 $6 6. Ne5 $1 {A strong and concrete idea - from now on Black has to reckon with g2-g4!} c6 ( Nc6 $6 7. Bb5 $16  ) ( e6 7. g4 Bg6 8. h4 Nbd7 9. Nxd7 Qxd7 10. h5 Be4 11. Nxe4 Nxe4 12. Bg2 f5 13. Be3 O-O-O 14. c3 $16  ) 7. g4 $1 Be6 ( Bg6 8. h4 $16  ) 8. g5 {(seizing more space)} Nfd7 ( {remarkable is} Nd5 $6 9. Ne4 Qc7 10. c4 Nb6 11. g6 $1 hxg6 12. Ng5 $16  ) 9. Nc4 ( 10. Ne4 Qc7  ) Qc7 ( Bxc4 10. Bxc4 e6 11. Bb3 $16  ) 10. Qf3 Nb6 11. Bf4 Qd7 ( Qc8 12. Ne3 $16  ) 12. Nxb6 ( {there is no need for experiments like} 13. Ne5 $6 Qxd4 14. Rd1 Qc5 15. Bh3 N8d7 $13  ) axb6 13. Qe3 ( {an interesting option is} 14. Bg2 $5 Qxd4 15. O-O Qc5 16. Rfe1 $40  ) Bf5 14. O-O-O e6 15. Bc4 b5 16. Bb3 $16  ) 6. h3 $1 Bh5 ( Bxf3 7. Qxf3 {We have already analyzed the analogous situation in the variation with 3...Qd8. The more active queen's location does not bring any dividents to Black at all:} c6 ( Nc6 $6 8. Bf4 $1 $146 {A natural improvement.} Nxd4 ( Qe6+ 9. Be3 O-O-O ( {one move later} Nxd4 $2 10. Qxb7 {is hopeless, for} Nxc2+ 11. Kd2 {will drop a piece at least}  ) 10. O-O-O $16  ) ( Qxd4 9. Nb5 Qxb2 10. Nxc7+ Kd8 11. Rd1+ Kc8 12. Nxa8 Nd4 13. Rxd4 Qxd4 14. Ba6 $1 $18 bxa6 15. Qc6+ {with mate to follow}  ) 9. Qxb7 Nxc2+ 10. Ke2 Nd4+ 11. Kd1 Qxf4 12. Qxa8+ Kd7 13. Qxa7 $16  ) 8. Bf4 $1 {Obviously better than} ( 9. Be3 e6 10. O-O-O $14  ) Qxd4 {[#]} ( Qd8 {means an escape to the 3...Qd8-line, even